    "markdown": "# Ch. 3: Tasks & Quizzes {.unnumbered}\n\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\nTo help us remember the different, systematic ways to use letter case, hyphens, and underscores in file and variable naming conventions, these patterns have fun names.\n\n![[Artwork CC BY 4.0 \\@allison_horst](https://twitter.com/allison_horst))](images/AHorst_InThatCase.png){fig-alt=\"Cartoon representations of common cases in coding. A snake screams \\\"SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE\\\" into the face of a camel (wearing ear muffs) with \\\"camelCase\\\" written along its back. Vegetables on a skewer spell out \\\"kebab-case\\\" (words on a skewer). A mellow, happy looking snake has text \\\"snake_case\\\" along it.\"}\n\n[**Q3.1**]{style=\"color:green;\"} In which case is this filename? `my_first_file_name.R`\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q3_1\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q3_1()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q3_1\" id=\"answer_Q3_1_1\" value=\"UpperCamel\"/>\nUpperCamel\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q3_1\" id=\"answer_Q3_1_2\" value=\"camelCase\"/>\ncamelCase\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q3_1\" id=\"answer_Q3_1_3\" value=\"UPPER_SNAKE\"/>\nUPPER_SNAKE\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q3_1\" id=\"answer_Q3_1_4\" value=\"kebab-case\"/>\nkebab-case\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q3_1\" id=\"answer_Q3_1_5\" value=\"lower_snake\"/>\nlower_snake\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q3_1\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q3_1() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q3_1']['answer_Q3_1'].value;if (x == 'lower_snake'){text = 'That’s right!';} else {text = 'That’s incorrect. Pay attention to the spelling of the answer options.';} document.getElementById('result_Q3_1').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q3_1').innerText == 'That’s right!';text = res1;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n[**Q3.2**]{style=\"color:green;\"} Why is this filename problematic? `MyDocument final.1a.docx`\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q3_2\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q3_2()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_2_1\" value=\"Mixed capitalisation\"/>\nMixed capitalisation\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_2_2\" value=\"Use of special character other than _ or -\"/>\nUse of special character other than _ or -\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_2_3\" value=\"Lack of clarity\"/>\nLack of clarity\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_2_4\" value=\"Spaces in filename\"/>\nSpaces in filename\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q3_2\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q3_2() {var text; var x1 = document.getElementById('answer_Q3_2_1'); var x2 = document.getElementById('answer_Q3_2_2'); var x3 = document.getElementById('answer_Q3_2_3'); var x4 = document.getElementById('answer_Q3_2_4'); if (x1.checked == true&x2.checked == true&x3.checked == true&x4.checked == true){text = 'That’s right! This filename is problematic due to the fact that it contains spaces, that it is unclear what ‘MyDocument’ and ‘final’ mean, and the use of the dot, which should only be used as part of the file extension. While mixed capitalisation will not cause any errors, it is not good filenaming practice and should therefore be avoided.';} else {text = 'Not quite. There are a lot of issues with this filename!';} document.getElementById('result_Q3_2').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q3_1').innerText == 'That’s right!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q3_2').innerText == 'That’s right! This filename is problematic due to the fact that it contains spaces, that it is unclear what ‘MyDocument’ and ‘final’ mean, and the use of the dot, which should only be used as part of the file extension. While mixed capitalisation will not cause any errors, it is not good filenaming practice and should therefore be avoided.';text = res1 + res2;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n[**Q3.3**]{style=\"color:green;\"} Which of these filenames are both human-friendly and computer-friendly?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q3_3\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q3_3()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_3_1\" value=\"Analysis_24April.R\"/>\nAnalysis_24April.R\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_3_2\" value=\"MANUSCRIPT_CORRECTIONS.docx\"/>\nMANUSCRIPT_CORRECTIONS.docx\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_3_3\" value=\"MC1.png\"/>\nMC1.png\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_3_4\" value=\"2024-01-05_TermPaper.docx\"/>\n2024-01-05_TermPaper.docx\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q3_3_5\" value=\"05.01.24_Draft.docx\"/>\n05.01.24_Draft.docx\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q3_3\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q3_3() {var text; var x1 = document.getElementById('answer_Q3_3_1'); var x2 = doc